## Explanation:

### Solution 01

- ***Brute force solution*** //not recommended.
- Here every iteration we’re sorting the array & changing the last 2 values.
- As the last 2 are the max elements, so ***x=stones[n-2]*** & ***y=stones[n-1].***
- We’ll replace x with 0 (as all elements will be greater than 0), and y with y-x.
- Return the last element after n iteration.
- **Time complexity:** O(n^2logn).

### Solution 02

- Using ***Max Heap.***
- Max heap keeps the maximum element on top.
- First, we’ll push all the elements of stones to our max heap.
- Now until the size of our heap won’t became 1 we’ll continue this operation:
    - Take the top element to y & pop that element. `y = q.top(); q.pop();`
    - Similarly, put the next element to x & pop it. `x = q.top(); q.pop();`
    - Now smallest element will destroy & we’ll push y-x to our heap again. In the case of same weight elements, it will automatically push 0. `q.push(y-x);`
    - When the size of the heap became 1 we’ll break the loop and return top element.
- **Time complexity:** O(nlogn).

---

