# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
* Simple application on priority queues. 
* All we just need to get the biggest two elements in the priority queue, and then check if both are equal, get rid of both of them, else, insert the new stone with the new value. 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
* Create a priority queue of integers. 
* insert all elements in it. 
* while there are still some stones :
    * get the top element with biggest value. 
    * remove it from the queue
    * if there are no more stones, return that stone. 
    * else get the second stone. 
    * check if both are equal, then just continue. 
    * else check which is smaller, then subtract it from the bigger, then insert the result in the queue again.  
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
* O(n + m), where n is the number of node, and m is the largest possible value. 
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
* O(n) for the priority queue. 
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
   #define DPSolver ios_base ::sync_with_stdio(0), cin.tie(0), cout.tie(0);

int lastStoneWeight(vector<int> &stones)
{
    DPSolver;
    priority_queue<int> pq;
    for (auto stone : stones)
        pq.push(stone);

    while (pq.size())
    {
        int top1 = pq.top();
        pq.pop();
        if (pq.empty())
            return top1;
        int top2 = pq.top();
        pq.pop();
        if (top1 <= top2)
        {
            if (top1 == top2)
                continue;
            else
            {
                top2 -= top1;
                pq.push(top2);
            }
        }
        else
        {
            if (top1 == top2)
                continue;
            else
            {
                top1 -= top2;
                pq.push(top1);
            }
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
};
```

