solutions.content:
The problem is challenging in two aspects:
1. How to frame the problem into algorithms & data structures
2. How to implement it with elegancy & readability

For me, it's not obvious how to handle the case when there's no free server available. I think of using a global variable: time. Then increment time until a server is free. However this approach is very time-consuming. 

After realizing using a second ProrityQueue, I face the problem of how to make my code more readable. I started with using int[] to store all the informations: serverIndex, serverWeight, finishTime. Then I realized that this implementation seems messy in the lambda expressions of PriorityQueue. 

Then I have this final result which looks okay for me. 
```
class Solution {
    class Server implements Comparable<Server> {
        private int idx;
        private int weight;
        private int time;

        public Server(int idx, int weight) {
            this.idx = idx;
            this.weight = weight;
            this.time = 0;
        }

        @Override
        public int compareTo(Server other) {
            return (this.weight != other.weight ? this.weight - other.weight
                                                : this.idx - other.idx);
        }
    }

    public int[] assignTasks(int[] servers, int[] tasks) {
        PriorityQueue<Server> free = new PriorityQueue<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < servers.length; i++) {
            free.add(new Server(i, servers[i]));
        }

        // sorted by finishTime
        PriorityQueue<Server> used = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b) -> a.time != b.time ? a.time - b.time : 
                                                                  a.compareTo(b));

        int[] res = new int[tasks.length];

        for (int i = 0; i < tasks.length; i++) {
            // update available servers
            while (!used.isEmpty() && used.peek().time <= i) {
                free.add(used.poll());
            }

            Server s;
            if (!free.isEmpty()) {        // Case 1). we have a server ready
                s = free.poll();
                s.time = i + tasks[i];
            } else {                      // Case 2). we do NOT have a server ready
                s = used.poll();
                s.time = s.time + tasks[i];
            }

            used.add(s);
            res[i] = s.idx;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
