//at first, this problem seems kinda overwhelming, but if you start to work on one example 
//like I did down below, you will gradually figure out, you need two queues (with priority)
//to achieve this function ... it's a great problem, more like a system design i think.

//there is one thing I felt quite tricky to get right is the time, at first, I mentained a variable
//t, and tried to update it simulating the whole process, but then my code could not pass
//#36 test case, stuck on it for 10 mins.....

//later, I discard the time variable, and simply used the index of tasks.

//logic :
	//1. you want to use a idle queue as well as a using queue for servers
	//2. at every index of task, you first check if any servers can be freed
	//3. after server state are updated, you check whether idle queue is empty
	//4. if idle queue is not empty, swell, you assign the server with the first priority
	//5. if idle queue is empty, you go to using queue, you use the top element in using queue
	//6. you update this top element and add it back to using queue


class Solution {
    public int[] assignTasks(int[] servers, int[] tasks) {

        int n = servers.length, m = tasks.length;

        //index 0:server ID, index 1:server weight
        PriorityQueue<int[]> idle = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b)->(a[1]==b[1]?a[0]-b[0]:a[1]-b[1]));
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
            idle.offer(new int[]{i,servers[i]});

        //index 0:server ID, index 1:server weight, index 2:free time
        PriorityQueue<int[]> using = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b)->(a[2]==b[2]?(a[1]==b[1]?a[0]-b[0]:a[1]-b[1]):a[2]-b[2]));


        int[] answer = new int[m];

        //int t = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            int task = tasks[i];
            while(!using.isEmpty()&&using.peek()[2]<=i){
                int[] tmp = using.poll();
                idle.offer(new int[]{tmp[0],tmp[1]});
            }

            if(!idle.isEmpty()){
                int[] tmp = idle.poll();
                answer[i] = tmp[0];
                using.offer(new int[]{tmp[0],tmp[1],i+task});
            }else{
                int[] tmp = using.poll();
                tmp[2] += task;
                answer[i] = tmp[0];
                using.offer(new int[]{tmp[0],tmp[1],tmp[2]});
            }         
        }
        return answer;
    }
}






